President Donald Trump has issued a proclamation declaring November 8-14, 2020, as National Apprenticeship Week. In the proclamation, he highlights the importance of apprenticeships in providing American workers with tangible skills and industry-recognized credentials. Apprenticeships are seen as a way to strengthen the nation's economy and help individuals support their families without taking on excessive student loan debt. Trump emphasizes his administration's commitment to supporting initiatives that empower Americans and prepare workers for success in the 21st-century economy. He mentions the Executive Order on Expanding Apprenticeships in America, the Department of Labor's investment in occupational skills education, and the goal of reaching 1 million new apprentices by next year. The President also mentions the Industry-Recognized Apprenticeship Program model, which offers industry-led training in high-demand sectors, as well as the expansion of apprenticeship opportunities for military service members. Trump highlights the Pledge to America's Workers initiative, which aims to provide workers with the necessary skills for today's economy. He points out the role of apprenticeships in responding to the challenges of the COVID-19 pandemic and emphasizes the resilience of the American worker and economy. The proclamation encourages individuals, business leaders, and government officials to support apprenticeship education and training to promote economic opportunity.